            {
               "text": "<h3>The Ancient Babylonian World Map</h3>Our understanding of the world has evolved over time. In antiquity, people represented the \"world\" as their immediate surroundings, rather than as the planet Earth as we know it today. The image in this section shows the world as envisioned by the Babylonians. In the next section, we project this map onto a modern world map to facilitate comparison",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 0,
                     "uuid": "5e23a3eb-7323-44ab-b9e1-88acfd1e21a6",
                     "text": "<i>The British Museum</i>",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "81161bc9-dd2a-4a11-906d-10427a5946d6",
                     "text": "Finkel, I.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection: External Influences</b><br /><br />As we began studying trigonometry, we noted measures like the famous \"Pythagorean theorem\" was already known by the Babylonians over a millennium before the Greeks. This fact raises the possibility that the Greeks either acquired this knowledge from other civilizations or independently arrived at the same conclusions more than a thousand years later (<htcite0>).<br /><br />However, the exchange of knowledge is not limited to mathematics. Dr. Irving Finkel, in explaining the map featured in this section, also references a cuneiform text preserved in the British Museum. This text makes mention, among other things, of an Ark and its dimensions. Finkel points out a shared element between the map and this text: the word <i>parsiktu</i>, which denotes a unit of volume (<htcite1> ; <htcite2>).<br /><br />Additionally, Dr. Finkel notes that one of the mountains mentioned on the map is near a region called Urartu—located in present-day Armenia, Türkiye, and Iran—which corresponds to \"Ararat\" mentioned in the book of Genesis in the Hebrew text. Given the way the Pentateuch was composed, it is possible that Babylonian traditions influenced later Jewish narratives, as Dr. Finkel suggests (<htcite3> ;  <htcite4> ; <htcite5>; <htcite6>).<br /><br />These archaeological discoveries demonstrate how stories and beliefs were exchanged among neighboring cultures and civilizations. Could it be possible, then, that these cultural influences extended even further, deeply shaping the traditions of distant peoples as they rewrote their own histories?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "5488872a-27c1-4ea8-8580-2ecc5aeb0cbf",
                     "text": "Mansfield, D. F.",
